<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN386-intro">
      <p type="edition">tiṇaiyum tuṟaiyum avai. cōḻaṉ kuḷaḻaṟṟattuttuñciya kiḷḷivaḷavaṉaik kōvūrkiḻār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en" type="translation">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div xml:id="PN386">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>neṭunīra niṟaikayattup</l>
<l>paṭumārit tuḷipōla</l>
<l>neytuḷḷiya vaṟaimukakkavuñ</l>
<l>cūṭu kiḻittu vāṭūṉ micaiyavu</l>
<l>mūṉkoṇṭa veṇmaṇṭai</l>
<l>yāṉpayattāṉ muṟṟaḻippavum</l>
<l>veytuṇṭa viyarppallatu</l>
<l>ceytoḻilāṉ viyarppaṟiyāmai</l>
<l>yīttō ṉentai yicaitaṉa tāka</l>
<l>vayalē, nelliṉ vēli nīṭiya karumpiṉ</l>
<l>pāttip paṉmalarp pūtta tumpiṉa</l>
<l>puṟavē, pullaruntu pallāyattāṉ</l>
<l>villirunta veṅkuṟumpiṉṟu</l>
<l>kaṭalē, kāṟanta kalaṉeṇṇuvōr</l>
<l>kāṉaṟ puṉṉaic ciṉainilaik kuntu</l>
<l>kaḻiyē, ciṟuveḷ ḷuppiṉ koḷḷai cāṟṟip</l>
<l>peruṅkaṉaṉṉāṭ ṭumaṇolikkun</l>
<l>taṉṉa naṉṉāṭṭup porunam yāmē</l>
<l>porāap porunarēm</l>
<l>kuṇanticai niṉṟu kuṭamutaṟ celiṉuṅ</l>
<l>kuṭaticai niṉṟu kuṇamutaṟ celiṉum</l>
<l>vaṭaticai niṉṟu teṉvayiṟ celiṉun</l>
<l>teṉṟicai niṉṟu kuṟukātu nīṭiṉum</l>
<l>yāṇṭu niṟka veḷḷiyām</l>
<l>vēṇṭiya tuṇarntōṉ ṟāḷvā ḻiyavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="9a">He who gives </l>
<l corresp="2">like the drops from a falling shower </l>
<l corresp="1">into a full pond with long[-lasting] water, </l>
<l corresp="3">so that we draw fried meat dripping with ghee, </l>
<l corresp="4">eat dried meat, tearing roasted meat, </l>
<l corresp="6">and wholly demolish the yield of the cow </l>
<l corresp="5">in the white/empty bowls that had held [those] viands, </l>
<l corresp="7">apart from the sweat when eating what is hot, </l>
<l corresp="8">in ignorance of sweating by work that is done, </l>
<l corresp="9">is our father. Since [such] fame is his, </l>
<l>in the fields, the sections of sugarcane are full </l>
<l>of many blooming flowers grown long as a fence for paddy; (10f.)</l>
<l corresp="12">in the woodlands, with the many cow herds that eat grass </l>
<l corresp="13">there is a fierce stronghold where bows sit; </l>
<l corresp="14">by the sea, for those who count the vessels brought in by the wind </l>
<l corresp="15">the branches of the Puṉṉai trees in the seashore groves are durable; </l>
<l corresp="16">in the backwaters, announcing the price for a little white salt </l>
<l corresp="17">the salt merchants from the good land of big rocks are noisy. </l>
<l corresp="18">In a good land like that we are fighters. </l>
<l corresp="19">Fighters that do not fight (i.e., artists) are we. </l>
<l corresp="20">Whether, standing in the eastern direction, one goes to the west, </l>
<l corresp="21">whether, standing in the western direction, one goes to the east, </l>
<l corresp="22">whether, standing in the northern direction, one goes to the south, </l>
<l corresp="23">whether, standing in the southern direction, one extends without coming close, </l>
<l corresp="24">let Venus stand wherever. </l>
<l corresp="25">May the foot of him who understands what we need live. </l>
</lg>
